   =20
      Papas don=E2=80=99t let your babies grow up to be investment bankers
   =20
 =20
I mean, fair:=E2=80=9CThe technology sector has just completely changed the=
 game,=E2=80=9D said Jamie Lee, 37, who worked in banking before starting a=
 venture-capital firm this year. =E2=80=9CThe opportunity cost is simply to=
o high to be sticking around in a job where you=E2=80=99re not getting the =
treatment that you want.=E2=80=9DMr. Lee=E2=80=99s father, the JPMorgan ban=
ker Jimmy Lee, was for decades one of the best-known players in his field, =
advising companies like Facebook and General Motors before he died in 2015.=
 But when the younger Mr. Lee was finishing college in the mid-2000s, his f=
ather urged him to avoid the analyst programs.=E2=80=9CHe said, =E2=80=98Ho=
nestly, J, the way that I=E2=80=99ve seen that we work these kids, I=E2=80=
=99m not sure that I want that for you,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Mr. Lee recalled.=
You could imagine a model in which one of the most influential investment b=
ankers in the world, upon seeing that investment banking was not a fit job =
for his own child, might say =E2=80=9Chey we should change how we treat our=
 junior bankers to make it a more attractive career that I could recommend =
to my own family.=E2=80=9D But of course that=E2=80=99s not what happened. =
You become a senior investment banker so that your kids=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t =
have to, and the way to make sure of that is to get lots of leverage out of=
 the junior bankers. You keep your analysts working until 4 a.m. to make mo=
ney for you so that your own kids don=E2=80=99t have to become analysts.Any=
way that=E2=80=99s from an article about how investment banking is bad now:=
But new college graduates are increasingly unwilling to put themselves thro=
ugh the strenuous two-year analyst program, despite starting pay that can r=
each $160,000. That=E2=80=99s especially so as careers in technology and ot=
her parts of the finance world promise better hours and more flexibility. T=
he pandemic, which forced many to reassess their work-life balance, has onl=
y underscored that thinking. Others, like Mr. Iyoriobhe =E2=80=94 who put i=
n 90-hour weeks at Bank of America, sometimes going home only to shower =E2=
=80=94 are willing to do it for the minimum time necessary to put it on the=
ir r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9s. He now works at a private equity firm.That paragraph =
conflates two very different outcomes? If banks attract a lot of top colleg=
e graduates to work in two-year analyst programs and then leave for private=
 equity, that is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0fine? Traditional? The model of investment =
banks as  elite finishing schools, etc. etc. etc., that=E2=80=99s how it ha=
s worked for many years now. Ideally you can catch a couple of the best ana=
lysts, take them aside and say =E2=80=9Chey you have a bright future here a=
nd PE isn=E2=80=99t really all that good, please stay here,=E2=80=9D but (1=
) that is hard because PE pays more and (2) you have to do that real quick =
because PE firms now hire analysts the minute they arrive at their banks, i=
f not sooner. (=E2=80=9CIn recent years, recruiters for giant private equit=
y firms like Carlyle and Blackstone =E2=80=A6 began wooing analysts even be=
fore they started their jobs.=E2=80=9D) Still, if your bank has a reputatio=
n as the place to go to train future masters of the universe, something goo=
d will come out of that.The other outcome though is that =E2=80=9Cnew colle=
ge graduates are increasingly unwilling to put themselves through the stren=
uous two-year analyst program, despite=E2=80=9D not only the starting pay b=
ut also the promise of a private equity job in two years.=C2=A0They prefer =
to take tech jobs or whatever rather than get on the banking-to-private-equ=
ity pipeline. The evidence for that is pretty anecdotal, and the story does=
 start with an anecdote about a guy who went to banking and then left for p=
rivate equity.=C2=A0


