lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Hmm</a>=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lordstown Motors Corp., the e=
lectric-vehicle startup struggling to find cash to move into production, re=
ached a deal to sell as much as $400 million in stock over the next three y=
ears to an investment fund managed by Yorkville Advisors Global.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The terms allow the Ohio-based truckmaker to direct t=
he fund to buy a tranche of Class A shares equal to as much as 30% of a day=
=E2=80=99s trading value of the stock or a block of $30 million, the EV mak=
er said in a regulatory filing Monday. When those sales take place, the buy=
er benefits from a 3% discount off the stock=E2=80=99s three-day average ma=
rket price.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hmm. The headline =
here is =E2=80=9CLordstown May Raise Up to $400 Million From Investment Fun=
d,=E2=80=9D but it seems clear that the Yorkville fund is in the moving bus=
iness, not the storage business. This trade is not =E2=80=9CYorkville will =
buy stock from Lordstown anytime Lordstown asks, in any amount that Lordsto=
wn suggests, at whatever the current price is, because it is a committed lo=
ng-term investor and doesn=E2=80=99t care about price or size.=E2=80=9D Thi=
s trade is =E2=80=9CLordstown can call up Yorkville anytime and say =E2=80=
=98sell some stock for us,=E2=80=99 and Yorkville will do that and get paid=
 a 3% fee.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, the mecha=
nics are[1]:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; =
margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Anytime it wants, Lor=
dstown can call up Yorkville and say =E2=80=9Cwe want $X.=E2=80=9D X is cap=
ped at 30% of the value of Lordstown stock that traded on the previous day,=
 or $30 million, whichever is less.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Yorkville says =E2=80=9Cokay we=E2=80=99ll give you $X in three days.=E2=
=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yorkville spends the next t=
hree days selling $X worth of Lordstown stock, on the stock exchange, to wh=
oever wants to buy it. (Presumably that means Lordstown=E2=80=99s retail sh=
areholders.) Yorkville is selling those shares short; it doesn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve them yet. Actually technically it is selling $X/0.97 worth of stock: It =
sells a bit more stock than it needs to pay Lordstown the $X that it reques=
ted.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">After the third day, Yo=
rkville give Lordstown the money that it asked for (the money that it got s=
elling the stock short), and Lordstown gives Yorkville the stock that it so=
ld (which it uses to close out the shorts). Yorkville is flat: It sold stoc=
k short for money, delivered the money to Lordstown, and got back the stock=
 to close out its short.=C2=A0Or, that is, almost flat: Because Yorkville s=
ells more than enough stock to pay Lordstown, and because Lordstown gives i=
t all of that stock, it has a bit of extra cash, which it keeps in the form=
 of a 3% fee.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Technically Yorkville d=
oesn=E2=80=99t buy stock from Lordstown at the price it sold at, but rather=
 at the average of the daily volume-weighted average stock prices over thos=
e three days, but if you are a professional investor it is not particularly=
 hard to sell stock at pretty close to the volume-weighted average price. S=
o if Lordstown asks Yorkville for $6 million, Yorkville will put in an orde=
r to sell $2.06 million of stock per day at the VWAP for each of the three =
days; at the end of that time it will have sold $6.18 million of stock, wil=
l give Lordstown the $6 million, and will make $180,000 for its trouble. Yo=
rkville also gets 371,287 shares upfront=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0worth $2.7 mil=
lion at yesterday=E2=80=99s close =E2=80=94=C2=A0as a commitment fee (in ad=
dition to the 3% it makes on any actual draw).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">To be clear, this is not a requirement of the contract; if Yorkville wa=
nts to keep the stock, it can. In practice though the plan is clearly for Y=
orkville to sell. Lordstown=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24569402.275148/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0F=
yY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTc1OTU0Ni8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjEwMDkyMjAvcmlkZS0yMDIxMD=
cyM3g4ay5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04a5beb7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">filing</a> says that Yorkville has a=
greed not to =E2=80=9Cengage in any short sales or hedging transactions,=E2=
=80=9D except that =E2=80=9Cupon receipt of an Advance Notice, YA may sell =
shares that it is obligated to purchase under such Advance Notice prior to =
taking possession of such shares=E2=80=9D: That is, they specifically expec=
t Yorkville to short the stock each time Lordstown asks for money.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also Lordstown is not allowed to sell Yorkville any=
 shares unless Yorkville can resell those shares freely under a registratio=
n statement. Also it=E2=80=99s not allowed to sell Yorkville any shares if =
the sale would put Yorkville above 4.99% ownership of Lordstown. That=E2=80=
=99s only about 8.8 million shares, worth about $64 million at yesterday=E2=
=80=99s close. That is not a problem, though, because Yorkville clearly pla=
ns to sell all the shares before buying them, so it will never own much of =
Lordstown.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This trade is sometimes called a=
n =E2=80=9Cequity line of credit,=E2=80=9D and it is not all that uncommon.=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24569402.275148/a=
