ZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB55f75495" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">works a lot like this</a>:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Aon=C2=A0PLC and Willis Towers Watson PLC=
 abandoned a more than $30 billion tie-up to create the world=E2=80=99s lar=
gest insurance broker, deciding it wasn=E2=80=99t worth pursuing in the fac=
e of Justice Department opposition to the merger.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The DOJ filed a lawsuit against the deal last month, the first big t=
est of the Biden administration=E2=80=99s more muscular antitrust policy. T=
he suit, filed in a federal court in Washington, said that the proposed mer=
ger would lead to higher prices and reduced innovation for U.S. businesses,=
 employers and unions that rely on their services. ...</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe reached an impasse with the U.S. Department of Just=
ice,=E2=80=9D Aon Chief Executive Greg Case said Monday. =E2=80=9CThe DOJ p=
osition is remarkably out of step with the rest of the global regulatory co=
mmunity, and we=E2=80=99re confident that we=E2=80=99d win in court,=E2=80=
=9D he added, according to a transcript of a video message Mr. Case gave to=
 company employees.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The prospect of a lengt=
hy court hearing was another reason for the merger=E2=80=99s demise. Aon an=
d Willis Towers had requested a court hearing for Aug. 23, but a federal ju=
dge ruled earlier this month that the trial wouldn=E2=80=99t start until No=
v. 18.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe inability to secure an =
expedited resolution of the litigation brought us to this point,=E2=80=9D M=
r. Case said. =E2=80=9CUnfortunately, while we requested a speedy trial, th=
e current course with DOJ would likely have taken us well into 2022,=E2=80=
=9D according to the transcript.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I have not read the filings in this case and am not really an antitrust =
expert; I have no idea if the Justice Department (which called the abandonm=
ent of the deal =E2=80=9Ca victory for competition and for American busines=
ses=E2=80=9D) or Aon and Willis Towers are right about the legality of the =
merger. The point is that if the Justice Department doesn=E2=80=99t like a =
merger it can delay it for years, and if you want to do a merger that is ex=
tremely inconvenient. So if the Justice Department decides =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=
=80=99re going to be 20% tougher on mergers,=E2=80=9D there will be fewer b=
ig mergers, even if the law does not change, even if the Justice Department=
=E2=80=99s interpretation of existing law is incorrect, even if all of the =
mergers would win in court, etc. Some companies just won=E2=80=99t want to =
take the time to fight in court. (This does not work for mergers that <em>a=
lready happened:=C2=A0</em>Facebook Inc. has all the time in the world to f=
ight the Federal Trade Commission=E2=80=99s=C2=A0efforts to <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24569402.275148/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjkvZmFjZWJvb2stdmljdG9y=
eS1hZ2FpbnN0LXRoZS1mdGMtaXMtYW4tYW50aXRydXN0LWxlc3Nvbi1pbi1tb25vcG9seS1wb3d=
lci1rcWk4amVrdQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB51638047" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> unwind its Instagram merger</a>.)=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything is like this. We have tal=
ked about the obvious=C2=A0fact that the current Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission does not like special purpose acquisition companies; it particular=
ly does not like how they use aggressive financial projections to market th=
emselves to retail investors. One thing it could do about this is make a ru=
le saying SPACs can=E2=80=99t do that anymore. Another thing it could do is=
 argue that<em> current </em>rules, properly interpreted, prevent SPACs fro=
m doing this; in fact an SEC official <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24569402.275148/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxseS1pcG9z/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB75219cf6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> has made that argument</a> (in a speech, though, not i=
n court). But a third thing it could do is just throw sand in the gears of =
SPACs: The SEC has lots of ability to hold up offerings, and it decided to =
basically slow down every SPAC deal over a very technical dispute about <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24569402.275148/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTMvZ3JhYi1z=
cGFjLW1lZ2EtbWVyZ2VyLWlzbi10LW1lZ2Etd2l0aG91dC1ibGFja3JvY2stcGlwZQ/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB7f1b8cab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> warrant accounting</a>. This SPAC slowdown has made SPACs=
 less attractive as investments and deal partners, and has done a lot to de=
flate the SPAC boom.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some limit, regulat=
ors are constrained by the letter of the law, but that is not always the im=
portant thing to focus on. If you are a company it is convenient to be on g=
ood terms with your regulator and inconvenient to be on bad terms. By shift=
ing that balance of convenience, regulators can set policy.</p><table class=
